title: LWC "Frilled neck FRAG V3" springloaded Airsoft BB shower grenade
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
UPDATE 15.11.2017
New type of ignition system ( bottom ignition only for best result in BB spread)
Even more compact now

New Pictures and video is on the way, stay tuned!! :)

UPDATE 07.11.2017
I was able to reduce the size of the Frag by almost 3 cm in length. that for I shortened the piston clamp arms, the Back-cover and main Body.

Airsoft shower greande " Frilled neck FRAG" new type of spingloaded Airsoft shower greande,

Remember that one scene from the classic jurassic park movie, where that frilled neck dinosaur spits acid in somones face? Well the frilled neck FRAG does more or likely the same, just with less acid and more BBs ;)

There is nothing like it on the market yet when it comes to the technical aspects of this airsoft grenade.

The FRAG will only go off if the lower bottom hits the ground ( or Whatever surface it is thrown against). If the Frag drops down on the side the ignition ballbearing ball will not fall out between the two clamps.

A few things are needed for this build:

1x 120x6mm aluminium pipe or rod
1x 160x10mm aluminium pipe ( NO ROD) with a inner diameter of at least 7mm or higher!)
1x 20mm washer with 8mm drilling
4x 45mm m4 hex slot screws
4x 35mm m4 hex slot screws ( if you printed the split base you need 80mm hex slot screws)
4x 18mm m3 cylinder head screw + nut
4x 40mm m3 hex slot screws
2x 35x2mm iron nail ( with cut off head)
common standard AEG airsoft spring ( needs to be shortened to fit)
10mm iron ballbearing ball ( slingshot ammo)
Dactape, soldering iron ( for melting the flipping arm screws into the base)
scalpel or stainless blade for cuttin the dactape into shape.

The 6mm pipe which runs along the middle of he main Body needs to be free floating,
That means that the pipe is only fixed on the lower side of the FRAG.
You can reach this by arching the pipe on one side, heat the arched end up a bit and press it back into the base with some force and glue or melt it into place. I used some pla filament heated it up with a lighter and " cemented" it in tight.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jePRai51v8

Main body should be fine in PLA, Parts like the piston, holding clamps and arms should be printed in 100% filling, ABS. PLA is more bridle and I cant guarantee if the impact of the piston is going to damage the arms.

title: Modular wall mount system for cans

description.text:
I designed this modular spray can holder system after failing to find something similar. All other options I've found either promoted laying the cans down (which is not awesome for the can) or were built for vertical stacking and took up quite a bit of space.

I therefore created a system for hanging cans that expands horizontally. The can is suspended only using a simple hook and no bottom. This works well by simply putting a rubber band around the neck of the can. The system in the picture has been working for me for several weeks and has yet to drop a can.

The system is modular in two ways:

  1. You can expand the number of cans you can hang on the mounts by printing interlockers and additional mounts and just sticking these together and screw them to the wall,
  2. The hooks are printed separately and slide into the wall mount which means you can design other accessories and attach to the wall mounts as well.

I've published two different kinds of hooks - one for a standard 400 ml can ("Spray can collar.stl") and one for the type of hair spray I use for adhesion on my printer bed which is a smaller 300ml can ("Hair Spray can collar.stl").

Finder

50%

Notes:

I'm probably going overboard on the infill but as this is supposed to take a little bit of weight over a very long time I'd rather have too much than too little.

I suggest gluing the wall mount modules together with the interlockers (cyanoacrylate works a charm, at least for PLA). This is not strictly necessary if you're ok with screwing every mount to the wall. I chose to only screw every other mount and gluing helped keeping the mount stabile.

For standard spray cans (400ml) with a welding collar at the top of the can there's usually not anything extra you need to do but to press the can into the hook. For extra safety and for cans without a collar I recommend putting a rubber band at the top of the can to prevent the can from sliding through the hook and down on the floor.

The most useful camera accessory I have ever designed and built has to be this fig rig camera steady. It transforms hand held camera shots and makes possible shots that are impossible when your holding the camera on its own.
To make the handheld camera Steady you will need

3D Printed Parts:
1 x 001115 Camera Platform Base
2 x 000714 Corner Foot
4 x 000709 Corner 135 Degrees
1 x 001117 Mounting Screw Lock (updated)

Non-printed parts:
1 x 1/4" Mounting Screw (with or without Ring) 0.39"/10mm Shaft
1 x M6 Plain Washer
1 x 1/4 Inch Threaded Diameter Insert Rivet Blind Nut (Optional)
1m x 21.5mm overflow pipe
Suitable glue (superglue)

Instructions:
Have a look at the attached drawing pdf for an exploded assembly view (001116 Fig Rig Camera Steady).
Cut up the pipe into 5 x 140mm and 2 x 150mm lengths.
Glue the 150mm pipe lengths into the base and glue the corners into the ends. Make sure you get then at right angles. You might find it helpful to glue a 140mm pipe into the corners first to judge the angle better.
Glue the remaining 135 degree corners into the remaining 140mm pipes and glue the frame together.
If your are fitting the 1/4 Inch Threaded Diameter Insert Rivet Blind Nut for tripod mounting glue this in place.
Thread the washer onto the mounting screw and insert into the underside of the base.
Glue in the Mounting Screw Lock to hold the mounting screw and washer captive.
Add camera and enjoy!

For more details including an assembly video please visit

description.text:
Ricktu has got a great idea to design a single line with contiuous cross section 3D fractal. It prints well when sliced with cura, but is not perfect when sliced with slic3r.

I then designed my own under openscad. It's a quite simple very small code using a recursive module.

Please, watch the video to see it printed and you'll get the idea of this fractal spiral mode object ! https://youtu.be/ihfkdBEPOOo

As it is designed with Openscad it becomes a customizable object where you can parametrize the width of the smallest pyramid and the fractal order.

  • size parameter is the radius of the smallest pyramid in the fractal
  • order defines the number of recursive iterations

The one you see in the first picture has been printed with a 3mm radius and a fractal order of 5. It's already a big object of 135mm which printed during 9 hours and 30 minutes.
[size = 3 order = 5] will buid a pyramid = 2^5 x 1.414 x 3mm = 135 mm of side lenght

EDIT 171117 : fixed a bug, now slices perfectly at size = 2

Printer:

ANET A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 with a 0.4 nozzle

Infill:

none - spiral vase

Notes:

You'll have to set your slicer to spiral vase mode. No top layer, one single bottom layer.

Layer thickness has to be set à 0.2 mm

what is spiral vase mode ?

the Spiral Vase setting of Slic3r will raise Z continuously avoiding a layer-change point which would cause a visible seam.

To allow this 3D fractal to be printed in spiral mode, it is needed that every layer is a continuous non crossing pattern. Which is the case here as every layer is a Sierpinski 2D fractal known as a Sierpinski curve. (see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierpi%C5%84ski_curve)

Sierpiński curves are a recursively defined sequence of continuous closed plane fractal curves discovered by Wacław Sierpiński, which is an example of a space-filling curve.

Finally, the printer will follow a single continuous line from its entry point (red arrow at the bottom layer) up to the pyramid summit (red arrow on top).

This makes a mesmerizing print !

comments.text:
Aha, the plot thickens!
Your gcode file indeed is printed entirely in spiral mode, but it is not printed the way it should be. If you compare the paths followed with the model (first image), you'll see that the little gaps are ignored. This is not a problem until the gaps again become large enough in the subsequent layers, that they are no longer ignored. Then, structures are being printed on top of the empty spaces from the too coarse previous layers (see next_layers image). This probably isn't very visible in small prints, but in larger prints with a very transparent filament, it could be. If the gaps wouldn't be ignored, there would always be something supporting the next layers.
comments.author: aeropic

comments.text: Good point! It's true that at the junction of the reversed pyramid and the new vertical ones there is a layer which is not sliced correctly even if in spiral mode, Slic3r only prints the external perimeter and the gap are ignored. I'll try to fix this...
comments.author: DrLex

comments.text:
The reason for this is described in bubnikv's first reply in the Prusa3d Slic3r issue #520: there is a hard-coded closing operation that has a threshold of 100µm. Ideally they should make this configurable, because even though I believe this kind of filtering is useful, 0.1mm is way too coarse, especially when printing with finer nozzles.
To fix this in your model, you should change the epsy value to 0.1, or you can make it a customizer parameter like I did.

title: Prop update for  Dead Space 211-V Plasma Cutter

description.text:
After seeing Ghost_3D's Dead Space 211-V Plasma Cutter, I just knew I had to make one. I Originally was going to print the design exactly, but after printing all the parts to just make it a wall hanger instead. Here are the modifications I made. Some parts you should be able to use on the original functional prop if you choose. Enjoy and make sure to check out Ghost_3D's Information:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1504670

Awesome how to tutorial by Ghost_3D:

high

Emitter section

I created more of a plasma discharge nozzle as I could not find any real images of what they looked like. you could run LED's in them and it's a bit shorter than the original laser design.
The nozzles are separate from the flat portion to allow for best print quality. The nozzles are just flush fit to the center and glued.

Lower pod

I machined an aluminum rod as I noted that many designs flex. This allowed me to hide the nuts as well. its total length is 22.5cm with 6mmX1.5 thread sections on each end. The front threaded section is 10mm long, the middle is 13mm wide and 136mm long, the rear section is 80mm long 60mm of that is undercut to 5mm to make it easier to assemble. To install in the front body part facing the nozzle of the cutter drill the hole out to 13mm wide and 14mm deep. drop in a nut and screw in the rod tight then glue the nut in. Be careful not to get glue in the threads! once its partially glued you can then remove the rod and finish gluing the nut in. to assemble. Screw the rod into the cutter first add a small amount of glue around the section of rod that will touch the body of the gun and tighten. For the back section do the same there is just enough flex to allow you to spin the read pod on. once tight visually check alignment is straight in line with handle and rest of the Cutter. you can then glue in the caps and smooth so the surface looks solid. The lower extension "thingy" I just filed it with a half round bastard file to fit the rod and glued it to the rod and pod.

Button hole cover

I just found and used a simple looking switch and glued this over the hole I then took a 3mm drill and drilled in just a bit to make a spot for a red dot to look like it's a safety or switch to change the Cutter position.

This device assists in spooling filament from a spool with a center diameter to another spool with a smaller diameter. The reason for its conception is the proprietary size of the filament spools for the Flashforge Finder but the principle works with any two spools of different size.

I've used the transfer connector together with the TUSH spool holder / rail https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2047554. I attached to sets of TUSH to a wooden plank at that right distance from each other using cyanoacrylate glue.

To respool the filament, stick the transfer connector's part A through the two spools. Then put the B part on the A part like a lid. Thread the filament into the hole in the empty spool and slowly start turning the empty spool, keeping the filament reasonably tense.

As you wind more filament onto the receiving spool it will become easier and easier to increase the speed on the spool. When you have enough filament on the receiving spool, simply stop and cut the filament.

description.text:
This is my Junior year machine design project for chico state mechanical engineering program. it is a bike hoist that is meant for limited space in an apartment or house to store your bike vertically with ease. The assembly is made mostly from Hatchbox PETG except for a few pieces are printed in Taulman 618 Nylon. This is an ADVACED printing project based on the materials used and the pauses that MUST be inserted into the GCode.

I used a 0.6 mm nozzle for everything but the nylon gears.

m3 washers may need to be epoxied to the ends of the two towers out the back of FrameFront4 because the screw head surfaces may be missing, I apologize if you downloaded this before I could fix the model and replace it with FrameFront5.

[UPDATE] 10-09-2017: I posted the STL file for Frame Front5, so if your downloading this after the update you're in the clear. Frame Front4 is missing very small yet important features to allow the 2 m3 body screws to do their job.

Where ever there is a m3 machine screw in this assembly shown in the photos (2 for body, 4 for motor mount, 4 for spool, 4 for battery door) you must find the layer that corresponds to the last open layer for the hexagon voids I created to insert m3 nuts mid print. Creating pauses during the print is crucial, to insert the nuts I partially threaded them onto a long screw and hit them with a propane torch for 2 sec so they can melt their way into the hole. BE SURE the nuts are below the surface of the part or you could damage your brass nozzle.

please notice that the renderings and photos have 2 pulleys top and bottom, where as this model is meant for 3 pulleys top and bottom to increase the mechanical advantage.

Color switching can be done to make the arrows pop out on the front piece. This will require 2 more pauses at the exact right layer, unless your using dual extruder.

Printed Parts:
1X Frame Front#, Frame Back#, Batt Door, Ceil_Bracket, Hook2, Lower_Cablegide, motor bracket, spool#, top pulley holder - PETG

(#) indicates parts that require pauses to insert m3 nuts

6x single pulley - PETG
6X nylon bushing, nylon washer - Taulman 618 nylon
1x BigGear - Taulman 618 nylon
1x DriveGear - Taulman 618 nylon

Hardware:
10x double battery terminals (amazon stopped selling the ones i used. Similar to these; https://www.amazon.com/uxcell-Battery-Connecting-Contact-Terminal/dp/B01E0CSUBE/ref=sr_1_27_a_it?ie=UTF8&qid=1507404802&sr=8-27&keywords=spring+battery+terminals)

1x dc female and male charge jack https://www.amazon.com/ThreeBulls-Pieces-5-5mmx2-1mm-Female-Connector/dp/B01N8VV78D/ref=sr_1_4?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1507404931&sr=1-4&keywords=dc+female+jack

1x Double momentary rocker switch https://www.amazon.com/Switch-Momentary-double-position-sealed/dp/B01CRI3ZAE/ref=sr_1_1?s=automotive&ie=UTF8&qid=1507404967&sr=1-1&keywords=double+momentary+switch

1x dc right angle gear motor https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01GHRMGTW/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

6x terminal connectors (small gauge)
8x 608zz bearings
10x rechargable AA batteries

1x Battery charger https://www.amazon.com/Tenergy-Universal-Battery-Charger-Batteries/dp/B003MXMJX8/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1507405049&sr=8-5&keywords=battery+charger+tenergy

2x m8x80mm hex bolts
2x m8x50mm hex bolts
8X m8 flat washers
4x m8 nylock nuts
6x m3x25mm machine screws
1x 14"x.125" rubber grommet
1x JST locking connector with 2 conductor paths
9x m3x8mm machine screws
15x m3 nuts (14 nuts heated and inserted mid print last one pushed into drive gear)
3x 8mmx57mm shafts (must be cut to length, same rod stock as most printers use)
small amount of 22awg stranded wire (~2ft)
spool of 65 lb test fishing line (80lb break strength, 60% strengh @knots)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mAbKNog0SMw&t=329s

Note:
-The battery terminals must be glued or epoxied to the frame front and battery door.
-one battery terminal should be cut in half with tin snips to make a positive and negative terminal. solder wires to those terminals and solder the other ends to the middle two terminals on the switch. The tops of the middle two terminals are also connected to the charging port so leave room!!
-polarity doesn't matter until the end when you wire the JST2 connector to the motor, the worst that could happen is when you push the up button it goes down. if that happens, obviously switch something like the polarity of the wires or the orientation of the batteries. that should fix it.
-also if you wire the charger to the male DC jack incorrectly, the charger I posted has a reverse polarity shut down feature.

good luck, happy printing! and try not to make a mess with your epoxy! please comment if you have questions and please post your make if you accomplish this project!!

description.text:
This is a new design for a top mount spool holder for the AM8. It will hold two normal 1kg spools of filament. This version simply sits on top of the printer so you don't have to worry about having to bolt it on. To use 8mm threaded rod, you may need to drill the holes a tiny bit larger. I don't know as I do not have 8mm rod here.

They will not tighten the nut a lot, but it'll snug them up so they won't move. It's easier than going to get a 1/2" wrench every time you need to adjust for different width spools, and they just hang on the 5/16" rod when not in use. **Do not use these to tighten the nuts on the two end brackets. Use real wrenches for those.

title: Prusa I3 E3D Titan Aero carriage with 18mm probe mount and part fan

description.text:
This is an X-carriage for any prusa-ish printer which uses an x with 8mm rods situated 45mm apart from each other (center to center), an 18mm ABL sensor and a 5cm radial part-cooling fan.

The carriage I print with 30% infill and no support. 4 top/bottom solid layers and 4 perimeters. The fanplate, same, but with support from build plate.

The carriage uses bolts for tensioning the belt against, this is stronger than printed plastic. Also it allows to use rings to lock the belt in place. Lastly, because it does not stop exactly halfway the bearing, but has a few mm extra, you can keep the belt running in the center instead of slighly off-center (as with the default carriage).

Before mounting, one has to drill the 3mm holes for the belt loop. They are not printed all the way through, to make printing without support possible. When assembling, push a M3 bolt through the hole from the extruder side, the head will sink into the surface. Then on the other side first a nut, tighten it, then the belt, then a washer and a nylock nut. Don't squash the belt between the nuts, the second nut is just a failsafe to keep the belt from popping out.

The fan is not screwed or glued. It just fits into the fan platen snugly, and then stays there. You might have to remove a small notch from the fan opening. If the fit is too loose, apply a drop of CA glue.

You'll need to print the model in parts, assemble it (I used a soldering iron - be sure to use a tip you don't care about - and some spare filament), then finish and paint it. This design can be a "standard" 3/4th enclosure mask, a full enclosure head or, with a little modification, a strap on mask. The enclosure part is intended to be tied on with string, cord or whatever you find fits the job. Also included are some eye graphics, however you will need to measure the eye sockets yourself and scale the graphics in your favorite image/vector editor accordingly.

The model has been sized to what I think is a good starting point, but it'll probably not be ideal for you. Resize as necessary.

I'd suggest printing with ~20% infill to get a nice, lightweight product. If you're planning to use an additive finishing method (resin filler or such), use the biggest layers you can print reliably to get the job done quicker. title: Top Spool Brake With Print-in Supports Anet A8 A6

description.text:
Ever have your spool unravel into a big mess during prints? I did, once.

Eliminates unwanted rolling for free-rolling top-mounted spools on bearings in either direction. Inspired by my experiences with twisted filament caused by the curvature of the spool. As the curved, rigid filament is pulled off, its natural tendency is to return into the coiled state. In 3D-printing, this can translate to the successful formation of a new coil off of the spool that can potentially ruin the print, several lengths of filament, and printer parts.

V2: More secure and substantial hinge, more durable/reliable, better aesthetics, zero-maintenance printed-in supports (still require cut out, but the "stilts" do not require glue to prevent tipping over during printing as they may in V1). Print as shown in photos.

I used some weather-stripping for added friction and a spring from an ink pen (see photos).

Note V1: The model files uploaded have improvements for durability and functionality, and are slightly different (and better) than my prototype (printed in red). V1 was left up mostly for reference of progress.

PLA
Print Speed: 30 mm/s
Fill: 25%

V1: Could only print successfully at 190 C, or else the print-nozzle kept tipping the "stilt" supports over on the build plate. No cooling fan until the first horizontal "bridge" layer, then turned up to 50%, and increased nozzle temperature to 195 C. Just use V2.

V2: Set to 199 C for a good bed bond, then turned the fan on to 50% after the first few layers and left it.

description.text:
This is a fully functional shower head with ball joint for adjusting the direction of spray. It is designed to be used with standard 1/2" threaded pipe which should be the most common found in showers in the US. It also has a removable end cap so that caps with different spray patterns or flow rates can be a used. The cap included at this time has 7 openings each 2mm wide.

I created this to replace a shower head that just didn't put out enough water. This isn't the best place to teach hydrodynamics, but most problems people have with shower heads have to do with flow rate and volume rather than pressure. Virtually all heads on the market today trade volume for pressure. The reason behind this is mostly environmental protection laws and are designed to make a shower feel just as vigorous without using as much water. When you have a flow problem like I did on my upper floor you cannot solve your problem with a head designed to increase pressure because this will reduce an already low flow even further. I needed one that increased flow without the need to increase pressure much if any.

With 2mm holes, I get plenty of flow (maybe too much) and I can finally rinse the soap out of my hair! I plan on experimenting with different hole sizes and patterns to find an optimal solution for my situation. I will make these caps available to you as I complete them.

For this to work properly you will need a #15 o-ring SAE (22mm i.d. - 3.5mm wall) and a 1/2" hose pipe washer. Wrapping all threads in teflon tape is also a good idea.

NOTE! - I have yet to print a totally water tight print and even when all joints are sealed, water may "sweat" out between the layers of the print. I have not had any leaks larger than a slow weeping.

Update: I have found the hole pattern and size that I like and have made a head that is solid (without the screw on nozzle pattern cap) to eliminate some of the leakage that happens around the threads. I have included this file as well if you want to just print the solid version.

description.text:
I wanted to make a separate spool holder for the Flashforge Finder in order to feed filament from non-proprietary spools. I found Phil_Read's excellent construction but found it a little bit too elaborate, and I didn't have a metal pipe...

Based off Phil's base model I've created a base that can hold a shelf (I use a wooden one I had spare) using an M5 bolt and a fitting nut (I use a wing nut myself). In the shelf I've drilled a hole and using a filament guide that goes in the hole. (I've made a couple here for a 36mm hole https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2573921, which incidentally was what I had in the garage, but here's another excellent guide for a different dimension as well: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2047638)

Finally I've put the filament spool on a couple of the TUSH Advanced (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2573518) that I've remixed from another remix off the original.

The result works at least as well as the built in filament holder thanks to reduced friction and strain to pull the filament as it is now being fed straight down into the motor.

To mount the shelf I put double sided tape on the bottom of the bases and taped them to the printer. I then put the shelf on top drew a light pencil line underneath.

I could then take the shelf and the bases off, turn it all upside down, align the bases with the pencil marks and use the pencil in the bolt holes in the base to make drill guide marks on the shelf.

After that I just drilled one hole on each side of the shelf, dropped a bolt in one of the holes and attached a wing nut on the other side of it and then I did the same on the other side.

description.text:
TRILOBE is a double-ended magnetic screwdriver bit holder, designed particularly for use with long-shanked bits like the excellent Broppe rounded hex set pictured above.

  • TRILOBE's compact size (20 mm OD and 30 mm long, or 25/32" OD and 1 3/16" long in þe olde unitſ) makes it useful in small spaces.
  • Its lobed design lets you turn the driver with your fingertips to deliver more torque to the bit than you could with a cylindrical bit holder of the same size.
  • Being double-ended, you can pack your two most-used bits into the same convenient tool, and you can use the opposite bit as a small-diameter handle to quickly install or remove loosened screws.

TRILOBE has two internal pockets to accept 6×2 mm neodymium magnets. Put a drop of super glue into each pocket, drop a magnet into each side, and seat them in the pockets with a stick. They will be attracted to each other through the thin wall and clamp themselves down. Allow the super glue to dry for a day, or else the outgassing of the glue will leave a residue on your bits.

If you find that the bits are a little too tight in the holders, heat the end of a bit over a flame and use it to stretch and smooth the walls. If the bit is still too tight, you may need to calibrate your flow rate.

title: 1" / 25mm Hose Adapter for 75mm and 97mm blower fans

description.text:
I made this for 75mm x 30mm blower fans with a 40mm x 30mm outlet and 97mm x 33 blower fans with 57mm x 33mm outlet.

Both versions meant to go into hoses 1" or 25mm ID. The mounting holes are meant for M4 screws.

It is printable with the large flat face down or with the inlet face down. Choose your orientation based on your printer's ability and the direction of stresses you expect the part to experience most. Large face down will stress your bridging ability, the broad upward slope of the inlet might be a challenge. I did not need supports for either orientation.

The part is meant to screw to a panel. The hose mount is offset away from panel to leave room for hose thickness. The large flat surface can be mounted flat to mounting surface with the hose connection protruding from mounting surface. You might want to use a hose clamp of some kind.

Designed in Alibre Design parametric solid modelling CAD. Alibre and STEP files provided.

description.text:
LED Lamp to cast light on the print bed. Designed with 2 lamp "shades" to house 4 plastic channels for an LED strip to run through. The channels are super glued (aka Cyanoacrylate) to bottom of the the shade. One of my 4 channels printed slightly too tight for the LED strip so I suggest test fitting them to the strip before gluing in place.

Shades are designed to be held on with T-nuts / M4-10 screws but I found they could be press fit into the top 2020 rail. STLs are rotated as I printed them to minimize (but not get rid of entirely) the need for supports, brims should be used for the channel / switch parts to keep them in place.

Electrical:
I used a while LED strip from here: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-Shipping-SMD5050-12V-flexible-light-60-leds-m-LED-strips-5m-lot-White-Blue-Green/1599651146.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.iGPCJx and cut it to fit.

I initially tried to wire it into the PS for the printer but found that the LEDs would flicker with load changes due to printer operation. Instead, I wired the LED strip to a pigtail ( e.g. https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CUKHN0S/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1) and a 2 pole switch I had handy (I think this is a comparable one: https://www.amazon.com/SPST-PC-Mountable-Submini-Toggle-Switch/dp/B007Z7ODBI/ref=sr_1_64?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1507840155&sr=1-64&keywords=toggle+switch) and a spare AC Adapter I had from an old network switch which could supply 12V/1A (something like: https://www.amazon.com/TNTE-Adapter-Power-Supply-2-1mm/dp/B0169AY3JI/ref=sr_1_2_sspa?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1507840580&sr=1-2-spons&keywords=12V&psc=1)

description.text:
Pebbling is a game where pebbles are placed on the vertices of a graph. A move occurs when one takes two pebbles from a vertex, discards one, and places the other on a connected vertex. A more detailed description can be found on Wikipedia - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_pebbling

In these simple puzzles the vertices are represented by shallow bowls and the connections, edges, are rods. To begin the puzzles two pebbles are placed on each vertex. The problem is to make moves so that a single pebble is left on the central vertex.

An stl pebble file is included although any collection of small objects can be substituted. OpenSCAD code is provided.

The vertices are numbered so that a record of the moves can be kept.

One puzzle contains 5 vertices and starts with 10 pebbles; the second has 6 vertices and 12 pebbles. Obviously 9 moves are required for the solution of the first puzzle and 11 for the second puzzle. The twelve pebble puzzle is more symmetrical and might be a bit easier as there is less opportunity for an incorrect move.

Other puzzles: One could invert the pebbling move; that is start with a a single pebble on a vertex, remove the pebble, add two pebbles to a connected vertex, and so on.
